	(98,1,'2016-04-18 03:00:25','2016-04-18 03:00:25','<h2 class=\"description\"><span style=\"color: #096faf;\">Alameda County – Sea Level Rise Inundation Mapping</span>\r\n<span style=\"color: #096faf;\"> 2013-2014</span></h2>\r\n<p class=\"description\">Under sub-contract with AECOM, BFA is assisting Alameda County analyzing the impact of sea level\r\nrise on Alameda County\'s shoreline. The goal of this work is to continue developing technical analyses and methodologies to understand shoreline vulnerability, and to apply the results of these analyses to the consideration of potential response strategies for specific, representative shoreline systems In order for the County to develop prioritized management strategies for their shoreline, a comprehensive assessment of potential sea level rise inundation and flood risk is needed. BFA is tasked with (a) performing high resolution aerial photo interpretation to delineate and classify the shoreline ,and shoreline assets, into five distinct inundation categories; (b) extract the shoreline overmappjng statistics, based on the shoreline/asset classifications and delineation and inundation models under 9 scenarios, and (c) compile a GIS database (with metadata) for final project results.</p>','Alameda County - Sea Level Rise Inundation Mapping','','publish','closed','closed','','alameda-county-sea-level-rise-inundation-mapping','','','2016-05-05 16:33:05','2016-05-05 16:33:05','',0,'http://fws.dev/?post_type=avada_portfolio&#038;p=98',0,'avada_portfolio','',0),
	(99,1,'2016-04-18 17:30:25','2016-04-18 17:30:25','','Alameda County - Sea Level Rise Inundation Mapping','Under sub-contract with AECOM, BFA is assisting Alameda County analyzing the impact of sea level\r\nrise on Alameda County\'s shoreline. The goal of this work is to continue developing technical analyses and methodologies to understand shoreline vulnerability, and to apply the results of these analyses to the consideration of potential response strategies for specific, representative shoreline systems In order for the County to develop prioritized management strategies for their shoreline, a\r\ncomprehensive assessment of potential sea level rise inundation and flood risk is needed. BFA is\r\ntasked with (a) performing high resolution aerial photo interpretation to delineate and classify the\r\nshoreline ,and shoreline assets, into five distinct inundation categories; (b) extract the shoreline\r\novermappjng statistics, based on the shoreline/asset classifications and delineation and inundation\r\nmodels under 9 scenarios, and (c) compile a GIS database (with metadata) for final project results.','inherit','closed','closed','','98-revision-v1','','','2016-04-18 17:30:25','2016-04-18 17:30:25','',98,'http://fws.dev/index.php/2016/04/18/98-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(100,1,'2016-04-18 17:31:51','2016-04-18 17:31:51','','South Bay Salt Ponds - Habitat Evolution Mapping Project','BFA was contracted for a three year pilot project building a semi-automated model to track the\r\nevolution of marsh habitats and mudflats (~30,000 acres) for the South Bay Salt Pond Restoration\r\nProject (SBSPRP). Habitat mapped as part of the study included mudflats, tidal marshes, and restored ponds; and to a lesser degree, managed marshes, levee tops and uplands. We mapped a total of 24 specific habitat types including 16 vegetation alliances and/or associations representing salt, brackish and freshwater marshes, 6 “abiotic” habitats (e.g. mud), and 2 vegetation types specific to uplands. A geospatial Quality Assurance Project Plan (QAPP) developed for the EPA by BFA.','inherit','closed','closed','','81-revision-v1','','','2016-04-18 17:31:51','2016-04-18 17:31:51','',81,'http://fws.dev/index.php/2016/04/18/81-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(101,1,'2016-04-18 17:32:36','2016-04-18 17:32:36','','San Francisco Bay - Transition Zone Conservation and Management - US Fish and Wildlife Service Coastal Program.','BFA has been contracted by the USFWS to build a GIS based decision support system (DSS) to identify and prioritize marsh-upland ecotonal habitats (transitions) for assisting land managers in restoring and protecting San Francisco Bay’s (estuary) tidal marsh ecosystem . The DSS takes a strategic approach towards decision support, by accounting for the landward migration of high marsh and other transitional habitats in response to predicted sea level rise (SLR). Current documents do not adequately describe ecotonal habitats, quantify the amount needed to aid listed species recovery while allowing for SLR, nor prioritize specific sites for protection and restoration. The DSS combines definitions bioassessment protocols, GIS models of the distribution of transitional zones, site specific criteria for ranking sites for restoration or protection, and parcels level maps for prioritizing transitional zones throughout the SF estuary. This toolkit will help managers allocate limited resources on site prioritization, alternative/scenario evaluation, and will include considerations for the influence of future climate change and land-use scenarios. ','inherit','closed','closed','','93-revision-v1','','','2016-04-18 17:32:36','2016-04-18 17:32:36','',93,'http://fws.dev/index.php/2016/04/18/93-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(102,1,'2016-04-17 17:35:58','2016-04-17 17:35:58','<h2 class=\"description\"><span style=\"color: #096faf;\">Solano Transportation Authority - Safe Routes to School (SR2S) Mapping Project</span></h2>\r\n<h2 class=\"description\"><span style=\"color: #096faf;\"> </span><span style=\"color: #096faf;\">2011-2013</span></h2>\r\n<p class=\"description\">Serving as lead on the mapping project, Brian Fulfrost and Associates (BFA), developed “suggested routes to school maps” for all public schools within Solano County as part of the county’s update to its SR2S Plan Update (led by Alta Planning and Design). The mapping project consisted of the following components: (1) develop a “pedestrian network” from existing street centerlines representing sidewalks and crosswalks; (2) collect data (virtually and in the field) on criteria identifying the “suitability” (e.g. marked crosswalks, traffic signals, etc.) for each sidewalk and intersection within “walksheds” fo each school; (3) use the network analyst extension of ArcGIS to generate “suggested routes” for each school; (4) automate a set of “suggested route maps” for each school using the suggested routes and pedestrian network.</p>\r\n<p class=\"description\">The maps were made available as downloadable PDF files, on the web mapping applications, and as part of SR2S brochures made for each school. In addition, BFA developed an interactive web mapping application (http://solanosr2s.ca.gov/app_pages/view/10) to view suggested and walking school bus routes, allow stakeholders to provide comments on routes, allow STA staff to update routes, and provide access to the suggested route maps for each school (as PDF). The pedestrian and bike facility inventory played a key role in the SR2S Plan Update to highlight and rank project needs, gaps, and priorities.</p>','Solano Transportation Authority - Safe Routes to School (SR2S) Mapping Project for the','','publish','open','closed','','solano-transportation-authority-safe-routes-to-school-sr2s-mapping-project-for-the','','','2016-05-05 16:40:59','2016-05-05 16:40:59','',0,'http://fws.dev/?post_type=avada_portfolio&#038;p=102',0,'avada_portfolio','',0),
	(103,1,'2016-04-18 17:35:58','2016-04-18 17:35:58','','Solano Transportation Authority - Safe Routes to School (SR2S) Mapping Project for the','Serving as lead on the mapping project, Brian Fulfrost and Associates (BFA), developed “suggested routes to school maps” for all public schools within Solano County as part of the county\'s update to its SR2S Plan Update (led by Alta Planning and Design). The mapping project consisted of the following components: (1) develop a “pedestrian network” from existing street centerlines\r\nrepresenting sidewalks and crosswalks; (2) collect data (virtually and in the field) on criteria identifying the “suitability” (e.g. marked crosswalks, traffic signals, etc.) for each sidewalk and intersection within “walksheds” fo each school; (3) use the network analyst extension of ArcGIS to generate “suggested routes” for each school; (4) automate a set of “suggested route maps” for each school using the suggested routes and pedestrian network. The maps were made available as downloadable PDF files, on the web mapping applications, and as part of SR2S brochures made for each school. In addtion, BFA developed an interactive web mapping application (http://solanosr2s.ca.gov/app_pages/view/10) to view suggested and walking school bus routes, allow stakeholders to provide comments on routes, allow STA staff to update routes, and provide access to the suggested route maps for each school (as PDF). The pedestrian and bike facility inventory played a key role in the SR2S Plan Update to highlight and rank project needs, gaps, and\r\npriorities.','inherit','closed','closed','','102-revision-v1','','','2016-04-18 17:35:58','2016-04-18 17:35:58','',102,'http://fws.dev/index.php/2016/04/18/102-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),
	(105,1,'2016-04-17 17:59:13','2016-04-17 17:59:13','<h2 class=\"description\"><span style=\"color: #096faf;\">Santa Clara County General Plan Update &amp; Health Element</span>\r\n<span style=\"color: #096faf;\"> Santa Clara County Health Department </span>\r\n<span style=\"color: #096faf;\"> 2012-2013</span></h2>\r\n<p class=\"description\">BFA teamed with Matt Raimi and Associates, Nelson Nygarrd, and Changelab Solutions to develop a forward thinking “Health Element” as part of Santa Clara County’s General Plan Update. BFA’s primary responsibilities included: (a) developing a “Healthy Santa Clara” GIS database including datasets on socioeconomics, the built environment (e.g. RFEI, “walkability”, access to healthcare, crime density, etc.), and public health outcomes (i.e. hospitalizations); (b) mapping a series of “healthy indicators” derived from the GIS database to inform the report; and (c) summarizing (in tables and graphs) these “healthy” indicators (for each city) by “communities of concern” and place type. The overall purpose of the planning process is to mitigate the existing health problems in the County, and to take steps now to prevent injuries and diseases before they occur. Each chapter contains a series of topic-specific indicators that provide information about the County as a whole. Data about individual cities is provided where available. The indicators were selected based on availability of data and known relationships to health behaviors and outcomes. Each indicator has a brief description, a discussion of why the topic is important for health, and an overview of the status for the county with supporting maps, tables, and figures.</p>','Santa Clara County - General Plan Update & Health Element for County Health Department','','publish','open','closed','','santa-clara-county-general-plan-update-health-element-for-county-health-department','','','2016-05-05 16:34:26','2016-05-05 16:34:26','',0,'http://fws.dev/?post_type=avada_portfolio&#038;p=105',0,'avada_portfolio','',0),
