	(292,1,'2016-05-05 19:02:40','2016-05-05 19:02:40','[fullwidth background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_parallax=\"fixed\" enable_mobile=\"no\" parallax_speed=\"0.3\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" video_url=\"\" video_aspect_ratio=\"16:9\" video_webm=\"\" video_mp4=\"\" video_ogv=\"\" video_preview_image=\"\" overlay_color=\"\" overlay_opacity=\"0.5\" video_mute=\"yes\" video_loop=\"yes\" fade=\"no\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"solid\" padding_top=\"55px\" padding_bottom=\"0px\" padding_left=\"0px\" padding_right=\"0px\" hundred_percent=\"no\" equal_height_columns=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" menu_anchor=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][one_half last=\"no\" spacing=\"yes\" center_content=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" hover_type=\"none\" link=\"\" border_position=\"all\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"\" padding=\"\" margin_top=\"\" margin_bottom=\"\" animation_type=\"\" animation_direction=\"\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][imageframe lightbox=\"no\" lightbox_image=\"\" style_type=\"none\" hover_type=\"none\" bordercolor=\"\" bordersize=\"0px\" borderradius=\"0\" stylecolor=\"\" align=\"none\" link=\"\" linktarget=\"_self\" animation_type=\"0\" animation_direction=\"down\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" class=\"\" id=\"\"] <img src=\"http://fws.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/brian_sfbbo-1024x682.jpg\" alt=\"\" />[/imageframe][/one_half][one_half last=\"yes\" spacing=\"yes\" center_content=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" hover_type=\"none\" link=\"\" border_position=\"all\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"\" padding=\"\" margin_top=\"\" margin_bottom=\"\" animation_type=\"\" animation_direction=\"\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][fusion_text]\r\n<h2 class=\"description\"><span style=\"color: #096faf;\">Brian Fulfrost, MS - Principal</span></h2>\r\n[/fusion_text][fusion_text]\r\n<p class=\"description\">Brian specializes in the use of GIS, Remote Sensing and web/mobile tools to assist in improved <span class=\"c2\">environmental and social decision making. Brian has 20 years of experience using geospatial tools to assist in utility operations, resource management, urban planning, and climate change vulnerability assessments. His work has supported a wide variety of industry, government, and non-profit organizations. Before moving to the SF Bay Area in 2008, Mr. Fulfrost served as the GIS Coordinator and Senior Lecturer in the Department of Environmental Studies at UC Santa Cruz, where he focused on the use of geospatial tool sin conservation and climate change modeling. Mr. Fulfrost has also extensive expertise applying GIS techniques to understand the role the built environment has on public health outcomes (e.g. obesity) and utilizing geospatial tools to assist in promoting “smart growth”. Mr Fulfrost currently teaches GIS and Sustainable Planning as an adjunct lecturer at SF State as well as Introduction to Remote Sensing for the University of West Florida.</span></p>\r\n[/fusion_text][/one_half][/fullwidth][fullwidth background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_parallax=\"fixed\" enable_mobile=\"no\" parallax_speed=\"0.3\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" video_url=\"\" video_aspect_ratio=\"16:9\" video_webm=\"\" video_mp4=\"\" video_ogv=\"\" video_preview_image=\"\" overlay_color=\"\" overlay_opacity=\"0.5\" video_mute=\"yes\" video_loop=\"yes\" fade=\"no\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"solid\" padding_top=\"55px\" padding_bottom=\"0px\" padding_left=\"0px\" padding_right=\"0px\" hundred_percent=\"no\" equal_height_columns=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" menu_anchor=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][two_third last=\"no\" spacing=\"yes\" center_content=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" hover_type=\"none\" link=\"\" border_position=\"all\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"\" padding=\"\" margin_top=\"\" margin_bottom=\"\" animation_type=\"\" animation_direction=\"\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][fusion_text]\r\n<h2 class=\"description\"><span style=\"color: #096faf;\">Dave Conklin, PhD - Principal</span></h2>\r\n[/fusion_text][fusion_text]\r\n<p class=\"description\">Dave founded Oregon Freshwater Simulations in 2015.  Freshwater is an outgrowth of his work on the Willamette Water 2100 project in 2013-15.  The WW2100 model developed in that project is the first in the Willamette Vision model series, which uses Oregon State University\'s Envision modeling framework as the backbone for an ensemble of biophysical, economic, and regulatory models of natural and human processes in the Willamette River Basin.  Freshwater is participating in the development of the second model in the series, which focuses on urban water use in Portland and Eugene (UWIN), and in the proposal for a third, responding to the NSF call for research on the nexus of food, energy, and water (INFEWS).</p>\r\n<p class=\"description\">In 2001, after a long career in industry, Dave turned to the challenge of modeling the effects of climate change on natural vegetation.  After 5 years in the trenches as the computer guy in the U.S. Forest Service MAPSS modeling team on the OSU campus, he returned to graduate school, completing a Ph.D. in Biological and Ecological Engineering in 2009.  Using the static biogeography model MAPSS and the dynamic global vegetation model MC1, he has run simulations of potential vegetation and vegetation change for a number of areas, principally in the western U.S.  He participated in the California Scenarios 2008 project for the California Energy Commission, in a study of Yosemite National Park for the National Park Service, and in several studies of areas in Oregon, Washington, Arizona, and New Mexico for the U.S. Forest Service.  In 2012, he reimplemented MC1 in C++; the resulting MC2 model has been used by Dave and by others at the US Forest Service, the Institute for Natural Resources, Conservation Biology Institute, and elsewhere for studies of many geographic regions, ranging from parts of various western states to the continental US, the south Asia subcontinent, and the whole earth.</p>\r\n[/fusion_text][/two_third][one_third last=\"yes\" spacing=\"yes\" center_content=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" hover_type=\"none\" link=\"\" border_position=\"all\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"\" padding=\"\" margin_top=\"\" margin_bottom=\"\" animation_type=\"\" animation_direction=\"\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][imageframe lightbox=\"no\" lightbox_image=\"\" style_type=\"none\" hover_type=\"none\" bordercolor=\"\" bordersize=\"0px\" borderradius=\"0\" stylecolor=\"\" align=\"none\" link=\"\" linktarget=\"_self\" animation_type=\"0\" animation_direction=\"down\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" class=\"\" id=\"\"] <img src=\"http://fws.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/image00-981x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" />[/imageframe][/one_third][/fullwidth]','About Us','','inherit','closed','closed','','122-autosave-v1','','','2016-05-05 19:02:40','2016-05-05 19:02:40','',122,'http://fws.dev/?p=292',0,'revision','',0),
	(293,1,'2016-05-03 16:58:19','2016-05-03 16:58:19','[fullwidth background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_parallax=\"fixed\" enable_mobile=\"no\" parallax_speed=\"0.3\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" video_url=\"\" video_aspect_ratio=\"16:9\" video_webm=\"\" video_mp4=\"\" video_ogv=\"\" video_preview_image=\"\" overlay_color=\"\" overlay_opacity=\"0.5\" video_mute=\"yes\" video_loop=\"yes\" fade=\"no\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"solid\" padding_top=\"55px\" padding_bottom=\"0px\" padding_left=\"0px\" padding_right=\"0px\" hundred_percent=\"no\" equal_height_columns=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" menu_anchor=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][one_half last=\"no\" spacing=\"yes\" center_content=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" hover_type=\"none\" link=\"\" border_position=\"all\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"\" padding=\"\" margin_top=\"\" margin_bottom=\"\" animation_type=\"\" animation_direction=\"\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][fusion_text]<h2 class=\"description\">Brian Fulfrost, MS - Principal</h2>[/fusion_text][fusion_text]<h3 class=\"description\">Brian specializes in the use of GIS, Remote Sensing and web/mobile tools to assist in improved </span><span class=\"c2\">environmental and social decision making. Brian has 20 years of experience using geospatial tools to assist in utility operations, resource management, urban planning, and climate change vulnerability assessments. His work has supported a wide variety of industry, government, and non-profit organizations. Before moving to the SF Bay Area in 2008, Mr. Fulfrost served as the GIS Coordinator and Senior Lecturer in the Department of Environmental Studies at UC Santa Cruz, where he focused on the use of geospatial tool sin conservation and climate change modeling. Mr. Fulfrost has also extensive expertise applying GIS techniques to understand the role the built environment has on public health outcomes (e.g. obesity) and utilizing geospatial tools to assist in promoting “smart growth”. Mr Fulfrost currently teaches GIS and Sustainable Planning as an adjunct lecturer at SF State as well as Introduction to Remote Sensing for the University of West Florida.</h3>[/fusion_text][/one_half][one_half last=\"yes\" spacing=\"yes\" center_content=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" hover_type=\"none\" link=\"\" border_position=\"all\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"\" padding=\"\" margin_top=\"\" margin_bottom=\"\" animation_type=\"\" animation_direction=\"\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][imageframe lightbox=\"no\" lightbox_image=\"\" style_type=\"none\" hover_type=\"none\" bordercolor=\"\" bordersize=\"0px\" borderradius=\"0\" stylecolor=\"\" align=\"none\" link=\"\" linktarget=\"_self\" animation_type=\"0\" animation_direction=\"down\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" class=\"\" id=\"\"] <img alt=\"\" src=\"http://fws.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/brian_sfbbo-1024x682.jpg\" />[/imageframe][/one_half][/fullwidth][fullwidth background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_parallax=\"fixed\" enable_mobile=\"no\" parallax_speed=\"0.3\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" video_url=\"\" video_aspect_ratio=\"16:9\" video_webm=\"\" video_mp4=\"\" video_ogv=\"\" video_preview_image=\"\" overlay_color=\"\" overlay_opacity=\"0.5\" video_mute=\"yes\" video_loop=\"yes\" fade=\"no\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"solid\" padding_top=\"55px\" padding_bottom=\"0px\" padding_left=\"0px\" padding_right=\"0px\" hundred_percent=\"no\" equal_height_columns=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" menu_anchor=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][one_third last=\"no\" spacing=\"yes\" center_content=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" hover_type=\"none\" link=\"\" border_position=\"all\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"\" padding=\"\" margin_top=\"\" margin_bottom=\"\" animation_type=\"\" animation_direction=\"\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][imageframe lightbox=\"no\" lightbox_image=\"\" style_type=\"none\" hover_type=\"none\" bordercolor=\"\" bordersize=\"0px\" borderradius=\"0\" stylecolor=\"\" align=\"none\" link=\"\" linktarget=\"_self\" animation_type=\"0\" animation_direction=\"down\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" class=\"\" id=\"\"] <img alt=\"\" src=\"http://fws.dev/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/image00-981x1024.jpg\" />[/imageframe][/one_third][two_third last=\"yes\" spacing=\"yes\" center_content=\"no\" hide_on_mobile=\"no\" background_color=\"\" background_image=\"\" background_repeat=\"no-repeat\" background_position=\"left top\" hover_type=\"none\" link=\"\" border_position=\"all\" border_size=\"0px\" border_color=\"\" border_style=\"\" padding=\"\" margin_top=\"\" margin_bottom=\"\" animation_type=\"\" animation_direction=\"\" animation_speed=\"0.1\" animation_offset=\"\" class=\"\" id=\"\"][fusion_text]<h2 class=\"description\">Dave Conklin, PhD - Principal</h2>[/fusion_text][fusion_text]<h3 class=\"description\">Dave founded Oregon Freshwater Simulations in 2015.  Freshwater is an outgrowth of his work on the Willamette Water 2100 project in 2013-15.  The WW2100 model developed in that project is the first in the Willamette Vision model series, which uses Oregon State University\'s Envision modeling framework as the backbone for an ensemble of biophysical, economic, and regulatory models of natural and human processes in the Willamette River Basin.  Freshwater is participating in the development of the second model in the series, which focuses on urban water use in Portland and Eugene (UWIN), and in the proposal for a third, responding to the NSF call for research on the nexus of food, energy, and water (INFEWS).\r\n<br/>In 2001, after a long career in industry, Dave turned to the challenge of modeling the effects of climate change on natural vegetation.  After 5 years in the trenches as the computer guy in the U.S. Forest Service MAPSS modeling team on the OSU campus, he returned to graduate school, completing a Ph.D. in Biological and Ecological Engineering in 2009.  Using the static biogeography model MAPSS and the dynamic global vegetation model MC1, he has run simulations of potential vegetation and vegetation change for a number of areas, principally in the western U.S.  He participated in the California Scenarios 2008 project for the California Energy Commission, in a study of Yosemite National Park for the National Park Service, and in several studies of areas in Oregon, Washington, Arizona, and New Mexico for the U.S. Forest Service.  In 2012, he reimplemented MC1 in C++; the resulting MC2 model has been used by Dave and by others at the US Forest Service, the Institute for Natural Resources, Conservation Biology Institute, and elsewhere for studies of many geographic regions, ranging from parts of various western states to the continental US, the south Asia subcontinent, and the whole earth.</h3>[/fusion_text][/two_third][/fullwidth]','About Us','','inherit','closed','closed','','122-revision-v1','','','2016-05-03 16:58:19','2016-05-03 16:58:19','',122,'http://fws.dev/?p=293',0,'revision','',0),
